availability.p: For internal use by the Faclair na Gàidhlig/DASG projects

note.p: A 16th-century medical and astological manuscript, mostly written by members of the Beaton medical family.

msContents.summary: This transcription file currently includes: (1) 11 charms from the first half of the manuscript; (2) Excerpts from the Latin translation of Averroes's Colliget, with Gaelic translation; (3) A letter from Lachlan Mór MacLean of Duart to his physician.

msItem.title: 1d: Charm 4
msItem.explicit: ... contra mulierem parturientem sin misi niall

msItem.explicit: ... agus leigtear do mar sin finis

note.p: Black (0061076) suggests tentatively that this is a particular type of toothache but, in the absence of further evidence for this, it seems more straightforward as reading it as the word "tooth" (dét) itself.

note.p: James Beaton (Hand14) adds a "d" above "tabad". This could be to clarify the meaning of the original suspension stroke or he could have been altering it to tadbad ("appearance"), although how the latter would fit in in terms of meaning is not clear.

note.p: The first 6 words of the text are now completely lost but seem to have been well-preserved when Black examined them in the 1970s.
As Black points out, this could either be the noun frecrae or the verb fris-gair. If the latter, it is an example of a lenited Scottish vernacular infinitive without do.
